      <div class="span16">
	<a name="motivation"></a>
	<h2 i18n:translate="headline-about-motivation">The Motivation - Why another collecting society?</h2>
	<!-- Warum möchten wir die C3S gründen? -->
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row">
      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="about-motivation-market-integration">Lack of market integration of Creative Commons licensed works</h3>
        <p i18n:translate="about-motivation-p1">
	  Musicians must be able to easily make use of the commercial option of free licenses without passing on advantages for non-commercial usage. Also, they must not depend on commercially available licensing platforms. A collecting society has no economic intentions besides those of its members.
	</p>
      </div>
      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="about-motivation-increasing-number-cc">Increasing number of works under CC licenses</h3>
        <p i18n:translate="about-motivation-p1">
	  Take the download catalogue of Jamendo, and you'll find more than 300,000 titles by almost 40,000 artists. Free Music Archive is offering about 25,000 tracks. In addition, there are various dedicated platforms and aggregators, netlabels and providers of free licensed music - all of them may benefit from C3S.
	</p>
      </div>
      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="about-motivation-cc-acceptance">Growing acceptance of Creative Commons licenses</h3>
	<p i18n:translate="about-motivation-p1">
	  Vimeo for example in cooperation with Free Music Archive offers a library of podcast suitable music. More examples you can find at previously mentioned outlets, but also at content providers such as flickr and YouTube. Moreover, in broadcast increasingly content is made use of and produced that has been licensed under Creative Commons (Link: http://wiki.creativecommons.org/Broadcasting). This can be observed at BBC and Norwegian NRK as well as with German NDR and BR, or Al Jazeera.
	</p>
      </div>
    </div>


    <div class="row">
      <div class="span5">
        <h3 i18n:translate="about-motivation-cc-nc">A large part of Creative Commons licensed works is using the NC (non-commercial) license</h3>
	<!-- Ein bedeutender Teil der CC-Werke wird unter einer NC-(non commercial)-Lizenz veröffentlicht. -->
        <p i18n:translate="about-motivation-p1">
	  Creators might want to allow for a free download for personal use. On the other hand, they would like to control licensing and distribution of their works, and they expect to be paid a fee for commercial use. At this moment, it's only providers like Jamendo or rightclearing.com (restorm.com) who are offering that. The other way is to negotiate individual contracts which are uncomfortable for both, the artist as well as the licensee.
	</p>
      </div>
      <div class="span5">

	<h3 i18n:translate="about-motivation-cc-unused-potential">The potential of Creative Commons is neither fully recognized nor are Creative Commons licenses deployed to full avail.</h3>
        <p i18n:translate="about-motivation-p1">
	  Fans and listeners of music are not familiar with benefits and concept of Creative Commons - if they know them at all. Moreover, it's often the same with licensees and artists. Even worse, Creative Commons services sometimes are mistaken for being unconditionally free of cost and entirely free of constraints.
	</p>
      </div>
      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="about-motivation-cs-cc-incompat">There's only a few collecting societies which are compatible with Creative Commons licenses,</h3>
	<p i18n:translate="about-motivation-cc-cs-p1">
	  or at least running test projects. Unlike in the United States, members of e.g. German collecting society GEMA may not license their works under CC licenses.
</p>
      </div>
    </div>


    <div class="row">
	<a name="goals"></a>
	<h2 i18n:translate="headline-about-goals">The Goals - What is C3S aiming at?</h2>

      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="headline-about-goals-admin">Goals in administration & organization</h3>
	<ul>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-admin-enable-comm-expl">enabling commercial exploitation of works that have been released under Creative Commons and other free licences</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-admin-represent">representing composers, writers & musicians releasing their works under Creative Commons or other free licences Europe wide</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-admin-vocation">democratic vocation by all members</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-admin-voting-rights">full and equal voting rights for each member</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-admin-non-exclusive">non-exclusive membership</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-admin-creators-performers">membership for creators and performers only – no publishers, producers or heirs at law</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-admin-transparency">thorough transparency in licensing plans, management and administration</li>
	</ul>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="headline-about-goals-service">Goals in services</h3>
	<ul>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-services-select">members decide themselves which of their works to select for administration by C3S - no collective administration</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-services-onetoone">introducing a 1:1 distribution of royalties instead of a statistical distribution key (applicable wherever possible)</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-services-minimal">minimization of administrational cost by highest automization</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-services-fee">membership fee: very low to none (freemium model); revenue in royalties as close to 100% as possible</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-services-maxservice">maximum in service for young and non-established artists</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-services-maxtransparence">maximum in transparency enabling the user to access all transaction data and user related analysis reports</li>
	</ul>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="headline-about-goals-general">Goals in general</h3>
	<ul>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-general-promo">promotion of young artists</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-general-culture">support of culture related projects</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-general-sustainable">sustainable support of members and culture in general</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-goals-general-openness">openness for new technologies and new business models</li>
	</ul>
      </div>
    </div><!--! end row -->

    <div class="row">
      <a name="funding"></a>
      <h2 i18n:translate="headline-about-funding">The Funding - How to organize and fund the project?</h2>

      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="about-funding-omc">OpenMusicContest.org e.V.</h3>
	<p i18n:translate="about-funding-omc-p1">
	  Temporarily, the working ground for our work and its base will be <strong i18n:name="omc-org-ev">OpenMusicContest.org e.V.</strong>. It enables us to work on building C3S without the need of immediately founding a second organization. Details on this, and most importantly which advantages and requirements this implies we have compiled in our KnowledgeBase 
	</p>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="about-funding-presence">Presence</h3>
	<p i18n:translate="about-funding-presence-p1">
	  We have been presenting C3S since 2010 at various events. This includes presentations and workshops as well as discussions and panels. Representatives of C3S have been invited to <strong i18n:name="sigint-2010">SIGINT2010</strong>, to <strong i18n:name="gvu-branchenforum">GVU's "DACH-Branchenforum" in 2010</strong>, to <strong i18n:name="popkomm-mediagate-2010">Popkomm-MediaGate in 2011</strong>, to <strong i18n:name="transit4">transit 4 at Augsburg</strong> and multiple times to Berlin's music conference <strong i18n:name="all2gethernow">all2gethernow</strong>. Moreover, we regularly are attending more events, such as barcamps, the Mannheim <strong i18n:name="future-music-camp">Future Music Camp</strong>, <strong i18n:name="reeperbahn-campus">Reeperbahn Campus</strong> at Hamburg, <strong i18n:name="c-n-b">c'n'b</strong> at Cologne, but also Germany's <strong i18n:name="chaos-communication-congress">Chaos Communication Congress</strong>.
	</p>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="about-funding-tasks">Tasks</h3>
	<p i18n:translate="about-funding-presence-p1">
	  The range of tasks is broad... and they are so substantial that we'd love to <strong i18n:name="add-you-to-our-team">add you to our team</strong>. We happily would welcome <strong i18n:name="support-single-limited-projects">support for single limited projects</strong> too. For example, we'd be glad to see someone draft a logo for C3S. Apart from that, there are opportunities to work out <strong i18n:name="studies">studies</strong> on selected topics in culture, economics and law. Unfortunately though, we won't be able to pay you for that - yet.
	</p>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">
	<h3 i18n:translate="about-funding-funding">Funding</h3>
	<p i18n:translate="about-funding-funding-p1">
	  For the moment being, all costs are covered by the team themselves as long as we are not invited as speakers. We plan to increase the number of presentations and to intensify PR which means an increase in cost. To allow for professional work, we have to finance these costs by additional resources.
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-funding-funding-p2">
	  The focus is not on funding our work for establishing C3S. We are working for free as of now, as long as efforts do not excess what's feasible. Yet, it is travel, accommodation, promotional material, campaigns and events that won't be available for free.
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-funding-funding-p3">
	  To cover our costs we deploy several resources. Most importantly, it's the membership fees of all the people being so generous and supportive to officially join <strong i18n:name="OpenMusicContestOrg">OpenMusicContest.org e.V.</strong> to help in building C3S. Of course we are truly thankful for anything you <strong i18n:name="flattr-or-donate">flattr or donate</strong>. Additionally, we are looking to find <strong i18n:name="companies-and-organizations">companies and organizations</strong> as sponsors and supporters. Finally, we obviously are <strong i18n:name="applying-for-grants">applying for grants</strong>.
	</p>
      </div>

    </div><!--! end row -->

    <div class="row"><!--! begin row -->
      <a name="roadmap"></a>
      <h2 i18n:translate="headline-about-roadmap">The Roadmap - How to get things going?</h2>
      
      <div class="span5">

	<h3 i18n:translate="headline-about-roadmap-realization">How will the project be realized?</h3>

	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-p1">
	  Anyone involved in the team has a full time job, dedicating their spare-time to C3S. All scheduled dates within the roadmap therefore are chosen to include a reasonable buffer.
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-p2">
	  The first and crucial aim will have been accomplished, as soon as we are ready to apply for certification as a collecting society at German Patent and Trade Mark Office (DPMA). In order to achieve that we are active in four directions:
	</p>
	<ul>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-roadmap-public">public - adding supporters and partners</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-roadmap-economy">economy - developing the business model</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-roadmap-technology">technology - modeling the workflow</li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-roadmap-law">law - providing the legal foundation</li>
	</ul>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">

        <h4 i18n:translate="headline-about-roadmap-milestone-1">Milestone I - Growing the team and establishing a base of supporters</h4>

	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-1-schedule">
	  scheduled for: 1st April 2012
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-1-p1">
	  At the same time when the website has been launched, our social media profiles went online. We are not just aiming at growing a community for a new collecting society of free licenses. We would like to identify active supporters and potential team members who are willing to work with us.
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-1-p2">
	  To volunteer in supporting us in this truly challenging project is great, and we really appreciate that. But those whose who will benefit much more are the members of the upcoming Creative Commons Collecting Society.
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-1-p3">
	  A range of options of how to support us, you can find on the support page.
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-1-p4">
	  As soon as possible, we are going to build a team of specialists being in charge of clearly defined tasks. Any crossover tasks are planned collectively.
	</p>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">
        <h4 i18n:translate="headline-about-roadmap-milestone-2">Milestone II - Presentation of economical, technological and legal drafts</h4>

	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-2-schedule">
	  scheduled for: 1st May 2012
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-2-p1">
	  The first concept on organizational structure and funding has been introduced in September 2010 at all2gethernow (a2n). Meanwhile, a multitude of details has been fixed or added.
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-2-p2">
	  Before finalizing our work on the public, economic and legal sections, we will be presenting our results for open discussion. Therefore, we have submitted an entry for the Call of Papers to re:publica 2012.
	</p>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">
        <h4 i18n:translate="headline-about-roadmap-milestone-3">Milestone III - Founding C3S as an independent association</h4>

	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-3-schedule">
	  scheduled for: 1. July 2012
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-3-p1">
	  Before applying for certification as a collecting society at DPMA, C3S will be founded as new and independent organization apart from OpenMusicContest.org e.V. As explained above, the role of OpenMusicContest.org e.V. will be changing by then.
	</p>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">
        <h4 i18n:translate="headline-about-roadmap-milestone-4">Milestone IV – 1,000 registrations</h4>

	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-4-schedule">
	  scheduled for: 31st October 2012
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-4-p1">
	  A significant number of artists willing to be members of and represented by the C3S are a central requirement to gain the concession as a collecting society. Our aim is to find 1.000 artists registering with us before we apply.
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-4-p2">
	  You can view the current number of registrations on the frontpage of our website anytime. If you didn´t do it yet you can pencil yourself in here.
	</p>
      </div>

      <div class="span5">
        <h4 i18n:translate="headline-about-roadmap-milestone-5">Milestone V - Application for approval as a collecting society</h4>

	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-5-schedule">
	  scheduled for: 1st November 2012
	</p>
	<p i18n:translate="about-roadmap-milestone-5-p1">
	  The final version of the concept will include the statute, the business model and a prototype showing the workflow of registration and royalty collection. Furthermore we´ll document the support we get from artists who are willing to become a part of the C3S.
	</p>

      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
	<a name="rules"></a>
	<h2 i18n:translate="headline-about-rules">The Rules - What are the principals we adhere to?</h2>
	
	<ol>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-1">
	    The C3S advocates tolerance. We will not tolerate racism, glorification of violence, pornography, discrimination of any minority and any kind of extremism.
          </li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-2">
	    The C3S advocates transparency. This applies to our rates and proceeds as much as to the administration, billing, balances and financing.
          </li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-3">
	    The C3S is governed and designed by its members through democratic prozesses and with granted equal rights for all members.
          </li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-4">
	    The development of sustainable structures is a premise of the C3S. We aim to become a relevant and continious part of the artist´s income.
          </li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-5">
	    The C3S supports creative activity and cultural projects of any kind. We especially encourage young and non-established artists.
          </li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-6">
	    The C3S opposes the criminalisation of private users. Internet-bans and lawsuits against non-commercial file-sharers are not worthwhile.
          </li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-7">
	    The C3S commits to strenghten the right to cultural participation for everyone. We do so by using user-friendly licensing concepts.
          </li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-8">
	    In case of possible copyright violation concerning works we represent the C3S will try to reach an out-of-court agreement before going to court.
          </li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-9">
	    The C3S will maintain completly independent to any third party. Political lobbying aiming at the C3S will not be tolerated. This goes especially for businesses supporting the C3S financially. Technology and infrastructure partner shall not be indispensable as well.
          </li>
	  <li i18n:translate="about-rules-10">
	    The C3S will question its aims, guidelines and policies on a permanent basis. Aspects not fulfilling the C3S and societies needs will be revised and updated.
          </li>
	</ol>

